Let's now calculate the present value of the loan if the APR is lowered to 4.05%.

$$ \begin{aligned}
PVA &=\$1,113.46\times\dfrac{1-\dfrac{1}{\left(1+\dfrac{0.0405}{12}\right)^{360}}}{\dfrac{0.0405}{12}}
\\[20pt]
&=\$1,113.46\times\dfrac{ 0.7027 }{0.003375}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{\bf\$ 231,824.96 }
\end{aligned}$$

Therefore, the result of our calculation is $231,824.96.

Next, subtract the present value from our previous calculation to the loan amount to determine the amount to be discounted. The following formula will be used:

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Amount Discounted} &= \text{PV Loan at 4.05\%}-\text{Loan amount}
\end{aligned}$$
